medication, especially if mixed with alcohol.','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(31943,2,'2-500-1','Factors Increasing Tiredness','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(31944,2,'2-501-1','Dangerous Microsleeps','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(31945,2,'3-501-1','Drowsy drivers may fall asleep and not even know it. They may experience microsleeps, which are sleep episodes lasting from a fraction of a second to several seconds. One of the symptoms of microsleeps is gaps in awareness. Considering that a vehicle traveling at 100 km/h covers almost 30 meters in one second, it is easy to see how a brief gap in awareness could turn into a fatal crash.','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(31946,2,'3-502-1','Lack of sleep can make drivers as dangerous on the road as drunk drivers. If you drive after being awake for 17 hours, you have roughly the same crash risk as a driver with a blood alcohol content of 0.05%. If you extend your awake time to 24 hours, you are as likely to crash as a driver with a BAC of 0.10%.','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(31947,2,'2-502-1','Fatigue vs. Alcohol','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(31948,2,'3-503-1','Drowsy drivers make dangerous mistakes such as:\n• Failing to maintain a steady and appropriate speed.\n• Drifting from lane to lane.\n• Following vehicles too closely.\n• Missing traffic signs and exits.','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(31949,2,'2-503-1','Under the Influence of Fatigue','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(31950,2,'14-504-1','Sleepy drivers are up to 3 times more likely to crash off the road than non-drowsy drivers.','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(31951,2,'12-504-1','Run Off the Road by Fatigue','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(31952,2,'114-505-1','assessment','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(31953,2,'33-517-1','the extra sleep you get after hitting the snooze button on your alarm','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(31954,2,'33-547-1','the more sleep drivers have, the more likely they are to crash','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(31955,2,'31-546-1','Which of the following statements about drowsy drivers is true?',