ood alcohol content of 0.05%','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(31975,2,'33-565-1','a driver with a blood alcohol content of 0.10%','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(31976,2,'33-567-1','a driver caught in adverse weather','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(31977,2,'33-566-1','a driver speeding 10% over the speed limit','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(31978,2,'33-909-1','a driver caught in heavy traffic','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(31979,2,'31-518-1','If you drive drowsy, you may experience which of the following?','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(31980,2,'33-519-1','brief episodes of sleep','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(31981,2,'33-520-1','blurred vision, or trouble keeping your eyes open or your head up','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(31982,2,'33-522-1','impaired judgment','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(31983,2,'33-521-1','wandering thoughts or daydreaming','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(31984,2,'31-524-1','Which of the following statements is true?','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(31985,2,'33-523-1','all of the above are correct','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(31986,2,'33-525-1','a good night’s sleep is the best way to avoid drowsiness while driving','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(31987,2,'33-526-1','opening a window is the best way to avoid drowsiness while driving','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(31988,2,'33-527-1','eating an energy bar is the best way to avoid drowsiness while driving','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(31989,2,'33-528-1','caffeinated drinks are the best way to avoid drowsiness while driving','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(31990,2,'33-906-1','none of the above statements are true','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(31991,2,'31-529-1','Which of the following measures do not eliminate fatigue but can help keep you alert until you are able to rest properly?','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(31992,2,'33-530-1','drinking caffeinated drinks such as coffee or tea','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(31993,2,'33-531-1','keeping your eyes moving and checking your mirrors often','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(31994,2,'33-532-1','maintaining an interior temperature that keeps you awake and alert ','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(31995,2,'33-533-1','all of the above are correct','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(31996,2,'33-907-1','none of the above are correct','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(31997,2,'31-534-1','On average, how much sleep do most adults require per night?','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(31998,2,'33-535-1','10 to 12 hours of sleep','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(31999,2,'33-537-1','4 to 6 hours of sleep','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32000,2,'33-536-1','7 to 9 hours of sleep','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32001,2,'33-538-1','2 to 3 hours of sleep','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32002,2,'31-540-1','Which of the following is a symptom of microsleeps?','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32003,2,'33-539-1','less than 2 hours of sleep','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32004,2,'33-541-1','shortness of breath','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32005,2,'33-542-1','pain in the legs','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32006,2,'29-979-1','Safe Motorway Driving','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32007,2,'217-16','Continue','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32008,2,'3-980-1','In this module, participants will learn:\n1.  The risks of traveling at high speeds.\n2.  Unsafe driving behaviors to avoid on the highway.\n3.  Techniques to manage highway driving.','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32009,2,'2-980-1','Safe Highway Driving','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32010,2,'2-981-1','Designed to Be Fast','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32011,2,'3-981-1','High speeds are always dangerous, and highways are built to be fast. While smooth turns and the lack of traffic obstructions help ensure motorists travel safely, these same factors can encourage fatigue and inattention, and tempt some drivers to speed. Many people are killed each year on highways in Asia.','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32012,2,'3-983-1','Highways are dangerous corridors that leave little room for error. Drivers must navigate around larger vehicles, which have large blind spots and sizes that can obstruct motorists’ view. When roadwork or a collision closes lanes, traffic can build up quickly along with drivers’ frustrations. For long-distance travelers, the visual monotony, repetitive patterns of passing lane markings and objects, and constant drone of tires can cause some to lose focus or fall asleep.','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32013,2,'2-982-1','Accelerating the Risks','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32014,2,'3-982-1','Small errors can turn vehicles into destructive objects at highway speeds. When drivers oversteer, they increase their risk of losing control, and since it takes longer to stop, they can reach hazards sooner and strike them much harder. Crashing at high speeds can be as destructive to the human body as falling from the ninth floor of a building. ','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32015,2,'2-983-1','External Threats','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32016,2,'2-984-1','Deadly Negligence','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32017,2,'3-984-1','Unsafe drivers treat highways no differently from other roads, but the consequences can be far worse. Injuries are more severe at higher speeds, yet some motorists:\n•  Fail to signal their intentions. \n•  Fail to properly scan the roadway.\n•  Make unsafe lane changes or last-minute exits.\n•  Follow other drivers too closely or exploit the open road to speed.','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32018,2,'114-987-1','assessment','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32019,2,'3-985-1','Remember these basic rules for driving safely on highways:\n•  Observe the speed limit or a lower speed appropriate for the conditions.\n•  When entering or exiting, adjust your speed to the traffic flow.\n•  Overtake other vehicles on the left.\n•  Avoid changing lanes unless necessary, and treat every lane change individually.\n•  Maintain sufficient space around your vehicle that others should not enter.','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32020,2,'2-985-1','Techniques for Safe Highway Driving','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32021,2,'12-986-1','Highways vs. Urban Roads','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32022,2,'14-986-1','The risk of crash injuries at highway speeds is at least 32 times higher than the risk on urban roads.','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32023,2,'31-1000-1','What benefits do you gain by speeding on a highway?','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32024,2,'33-1002-1','you reduce your risk of injury or death in a crash','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32025,2,'33-1001-1','you reduce your travel time by at least 10 minutes every time','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32026,2,'33-1003-1','you reduce the danger you pose to others','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32027,2,'33-1004-1','you reduce the risk of causing traffic congestion','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32028,2,'33-1005-1','none of the above are correct','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32029,2,'31-1012-1','What steps should you remember when merging onto a highway?','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32030,2,'33-1013-1','look for a safe gap in traffic','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32031,2,'33-1014-1','check your mirrors and blind spots to ensure the lane beside you is clear','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32032,2,'33-1015-1','signal in advance to alert other drivers to your intentions','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32033,2,'33-1016-1','merge when you have sufficient space ahead and behind your vehicle','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32034,2,'33-1017-1','all of the above are correct','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32035,2,'31-1018-1','When you keep a safe following distance, what is true?','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32036,2,'33-1019-1','you improve your ability to react safely to an emergency braking situation','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32037,2,'33-1020-1','you create traffic congestion behind you','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32038,2,'33-1021-1','you prevent aggressive motorists from cutting in front of you','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32039,2,'33-1022-1','you significantly increase your travel time','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32040,2,'33-1023-1','none of the above are correct','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32041,2,'31-1024-1','When driving on a highway, how far in advance should you signal your intentions?','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32042,2,'33-1025-1','once you begin a maneuver','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32043,2,'33-1026-1','1 to 2 seconds before a maneuver','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32044,2,'33-1028-1','45 seconds before a maneuver','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32045,2,'33-1027-1','4 to 5 seconds before a maneuver','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32046,2,'33-1029-1','1 to 2 minutes before a maneuver','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32047,2,'31-1030-1','After you pass a vehicle, what must you be able to see in your rear-view mirror before you return to your original lane?','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32048,2,'33-1031-1','the entire front end of the vehicle you just passed','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32049,2,'33-1033-1','one headlight of the vehicle you just passed','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32050,2,'33-1032-1','a side mirror of the vehicle you just passed','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32051,2,'33-1034-1','the driver of the vehicle you just passed','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32052,2,'33-1035-1','checking your rear-view mirror is not important after you pass a vehicle','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32053,2,'33-1037-1','treat each lane change individually when moving towards an exit','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32054,2,'31-1036-1','What should you remember when exiting a highway?','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32055,2,'33-1039-1','move onto the exit ramp as soon as possible','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32056,2,'33-1040-1','use the exit ramp to adjust your speed to the speed of slower traffic ahead','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32057,2,'33-1038-1','look ahead for exit signs and the correct exit lane ','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32058,2,'33-1041-1','all of the above are correct','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32059,2,'31-1042-1','When is it safe to exceed the speed limit on a highway?','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32060,2,'33-1043-1','when traffic is light or on open stretches of road','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32061,2,'33-1045-1','when you are late for work','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32062,2,'33-1044-1','when roadwork or a collision closes one or more lanes','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32063,2,'33-1046-1','it is never safe to exceed the speed limit on a highway','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32064,2,'33-1047-1','none of the above are correct','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32065,2,'31-988-1','Which of the following statements about high-speed driving is true?','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32066,2,'33-989-1','vehicles take longer to stop','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32067,2,'33-991-1','vehicles can become difficult to control if drivers oversteer','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32068,2,'33-990-1','vehicles can reach hazards sooner','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32069,2,'33-992-1','vehicles can become destructive objects if drivers make an error that results in a crash','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32070,2,'33-993-1','all of the above statements are true','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32071,2,'31-994-1','According to the module, crashing at high speeds','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32072,2,'33-997-1','can be as destructive to the human body as most illnesses','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32073,2,'33-998-1','is equivalent to a bullet hitting an apple','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32074,2,'31-1006-1','When should you start practicing highway safety?','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32075,2,'33-999-1','none of the above are correct','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32076,2,'33-1008-1','from the moment you pass another vehicle','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32077,2,'33-1009-1','only when you are changing lanes','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32078,2,'33-1010-1','only when you are exiting','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32079,2,'33-1007-1','from the moment you get on the highway','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32080,2,'33-1011-1','none of the above are correct ','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32081,2,'29-910-1','Sharing the Road With Large Trucks','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32082,2,'203-16','Continue','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32083,2,'2-911-1','Sharing the Road With Large Trucks','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32084,2,'3-911-1','In this module, participants will learn:\n1.    The dangers posed by large trucks.\n2.    How to avoid a truck’s blind spots.\n3.    How to share the road safely with large vehicles.','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32085,2,'2-912-1','High-Impact Hazards','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32086,2,'1-911-1','/media/courses/ddt/LTR/Global/Slides/IMG01.svg','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32087,2,'33-952-1','the driver of the truck falls asleep','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32088,2,'3-912-1','Sharing the road with large trucks is more dangerous than many drivers realize. Trucks have large blind spots, and their size makes them difficult to handle in emergency situations. A commercial truck is 20 to 30 times heavier than a passenger vehicle, so when a car and a truck collide, the car usually loses. ','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32089,2,'2-913-1','Trucks Are Not Big Cars','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32090,2,'3-913-1','Many drivers make the mistake of treating trucks like big cars, but a truck’s size and length make them extreme hazards all drivers should try to avoid. Trucks take longer to stop, are harder to steer, and their large turning radius often forces them far into an intersection or across two lanes. Many car drivers hit by a truck did not respect the truck’s size and weight.','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32091,2,'2-914-1','Unpredictable Hazards ','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32092,2,'3-914-1','Many of the dangers posed by trucks are out of your control. Truck tires can blow out or their brakes can fail, causing a serious threat for nearby motorists. In bad weather, heavy splash reduces visibility, and air turbulence from a truck can force a nearby car to lose control. ','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32093,2,'2-915-1','Who Is at Fault?','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32094,2,'33-954-1','none of the above are correct','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32095,2,'3-915-1','In car-truck collisions, it is often the driver of the smaller vehicle who makes the mistake, such as improper lane changes and disrespecting a truck’s large size and blind spots. Car drivers are responsible for the majority of car-truck crashes.   ','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32096,2,'3-916-1','The best solution to reduce your risk of a collision with a large truck is to avoid them altogether. When you do encounter a large truck on the road, making the truck driver aware of your presence will help keep both of you safe. This means:\n• Signaling during lane changes. \n• Giving trucks room to complete their maneuvers.\n• Checking mirrors and blind spots before passing a truck.\n• Staying out of a truck’s blind spots.','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32097,2,'12-917-1','Trucks Stop Slower','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32098,2,'2-916-1','Techniques to Avoid Collisions ','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32099,2,'14-917-1','Traveling at 80 km/h, some large trucks take up to 50% longer to stop than a car.','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32100,2,'114-918-1','assessment','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32101,2,'31-931-1','Which areas around a truck should you avoid driving in?','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32102,2,'33-932-1','on the driver’s side, either beside or just behind the cab','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32103,2,'33-933-1','on the passenger’s side just behind the cab and down the full length of the vehicle','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32104,2,'33-934-1','closely behind the truck','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32105,2,'33-935-1','directly ahead of the truck’s front end','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32106,2,'31-955-1','Which of the following is a factor in the majority of fatal collisions between passenger vehicles and large trucks?','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32107,2,'33-936-1','all of the above are correct','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32108,2,'33-956-1','motorists avoiding trucks\' \"no-zones\"','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32109,2,'33-957-1','motorists driving without the influence of either drugs or alcohol','en',NULL,NULL,'US',NULL),(32110,2,'33-958-1','motorists lingering in \"no-zones\"','en',NULL,NULL